title: Kentucky Football | Cats defensive tackle C.J. Johnson had 19 tackles vs. EKU
text:
LEXINGTON, Ky. – To call what C.J. Johnson is doing unexpected would be quite an understatement.
For starters, he began this season as a backup for the Kentucky football team. Also, he's a defensive tackle, a position not known for producing gaudy statistics. More specifically, he was not known for doing such things, having managed 10 tackles all last season and exactly one through Week 2 this fall.
But now here it is: C.J. Johnson, tackling machine.
Maybe all he needed was a chance. When starter Regie Meant went down with a shoulder injury in Week 3 against Florida, Johnson launched a three-week run of career highs in tackles: six against the Gators, 11 against Missouri and then … nineteen Saturday night against Eastern Kentucky, including the game-clinching sack in overtime.
"I need to get in the bed. Ain't no ice bath gonna do what a bed could do," an exhausted Johnson said after that jaw-dropping performance. "Yeah, it shocked me, too. Josh (Forrest) told me at first, when I had 15. I was like, 'Man, I gotta see how far I can go with this thing.' "
Here's how far he went: Those 19 tackles are the most by a UK defensive lineman since at least 1991. Defensive coordinator D.J. Eliot said he can't recall ever having a lineman make that many. And now suddenly, among linemen, Johnson leads the nation in tackles.
THE COURIER-JOURNAL
Cat-astrophe averted: UK rallies to beat EKU
The 6-foot-3, 300-pound senior has 37 total stops, 3 ½ for loss, a pair of sacks and a blocked kick.
"He's real quick and athletic," Eliot said, "and we stunt and move him around a lot (so) it puts him in position to make plays. It was a good job by him."
Johnson might not have seen such a super surge in production coming, but the former four-star junior-college transfer balks at the idea that this has all come out of nowhere.
"I worked hard for it," he said. "I feel like every time I step out on the field, I gotta do big things for my team, so I ain't surprised at all. I'm surprised I got 19 today, but I ain't surprised I'm gonna come out and play big."
Based on his upward trend, can he go even bigger?
"In high school, I had 21 in a game. You can look it up," said Johnson, whose Cats (4-1) are off until an Oct. 15 collision with Auburn. "If I get 21 against Auburn, I don't even know."
THE COURIER-JOURNAL
Instant Analysis | Kentucky ekes out OT win
He would likely make himself some NFL money if that happens. He might be doing that anyway with this recent outburst. That's the goal for Johnson, who said the only call or text message he cared about after Saturday's game was from his mother.
He aims to take care of her someday, and he views football as the way.
"Once I had the money in my hand," he said of the winning sack against EKU, "I wasn't letting go."
